<TITLE> UN polls assessment team arrives </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Nov 23 (bdnews24.com) The UN polls assessment team arrived in the city Sunday with a view to preparing a report for secretary-general Ban Ki-moon on Bangladesh's preparation for transition to democracy by December. The three-member panel, headed by Francesc Vendrell, former personal representative of the UN secretary-general for Afghanistan, welcomed the Election Commission's announcement of the new general election Sunday. "This is a very good news," Vendrell told journalists after landing at Zia International Airport at around 8.00 pm. "I am glad it seems to be that this date satisfies everybody," he said. "The reason for coming here is on behalf of the secretary-general to assess the electoral climate and report back to him," he told bdnews24.com. The other two members are of the team are Bhojraj Pokharel, chief election commissioner of Nepal, and Aracelly Santana, former deputy director of the UN's electoral assistance division. Ban Ki-moon during his Nov 1 Dhaka visit announced sending a polls assessment team to weigh Bangladesh's preparation for holding the next general elections by December this year. The members will hold discussions with key stakeholders to prepare their report. "The team will return for about a week at the time of the elections," a UN spokesperson said in a press statement. bdn
